---
import DocsLayout from '../../design-system/docs-shell/DocsLayout.astro';
import Card from '../../design-system/ui/Card.astro';
import Badge from '../../design-system/ui/Badge.astro';
import Button from '../../design-system/ui/Button.astro';
import Callout from '../../design-system/ui/Callout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../design-system/ui/CodeBlock.astro';

const breadcrumbs = [
  { label: 'Docs', href: '/docs' },
  { label: 'Getting started', href: '/docs/getting-started' },
  { label: 'Deploying a release' },
];

const sidebar = [
  {
    title: 'Getting started',
    items: [
      { label: 'Overview', href: '#' },
      { label: 'Installation', href: '#' },
      { label: 'Your first project', href: '#' },
      { label: 'Deploying a release', href: '#', active: true },
      { label: 'Environments', href: '#' },
    ],
  },
  {
    title: 'Deployments',
    items: [
      { label: 'Deployment process', href: '#' },
      { label: 'Variables', href: '#' },
      { label: 'Releases & channels', href: '#' },
      { label: 'Runbooks', href: '#' },
    ],
  },
  {
    title: 'Infrastructure',
    items: [
      { label: 'Targets', href: '#' },
      { label: 'Workers', href: '#' },
      { label: 'Accounts', href: '#' },
    ],
  },
];

const toc = [
  { label: 'Before you begin', href: '#before-you-begin' },
  { label: 'Create a release', href: '#create-a-release' },
  { label: 'Promote to an environment', href: '#promote', depth: 2 },
  { label: 'Deploy from the CLI', href: '#deploy-cli' },
  { label: 'Next steps', href: '#next-steps' },
];
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Deploying a release"
  description="Create a release from your deployment process and promote it through your environments - from the dashboard or the CLI."
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
  sidebar={sidebar}
  toc={toc}
>
  <div class="not-prose mb-7 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2">
    <Badge variant="brand">Guide</Badge>
    <Badge variant="outline">
      <svg
        class="h-3 w-3"
        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
        fill="none"
        stroke="currentColor"
        stroke-width="2"
        stroke-linecap="round"
        stroke-linejoin="round"
        aria-hidden="true"
        ><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="9"></circle><path d="M12 7v5l3 2"
        ></path></svg
      >
      10 min read
    </Badge>
    <Badge variant="success">Beginner</Badge>
  </div>

  <p>
    A <strong>release</strong> is a snapshot of your deployment process and the variables
    and packages it references. Once you have a release, you deploy it to an environment
    such as <em>Development</em>, <em>Test</em>, or
    <em>Production</em>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="before-you-begin">Before you begin</h2>
  <p>
    Make sure you have a project with a configured deployment process and at
    least one deployment target registered in an environment.
  </p>

  <Callout intent="info" title="Prerequisites">
    You need the <code>Project deployer</code> role (or higher) to create and deploy
    releases. See <a href="#">Managing users and teams</a>.
  </Callout>

  <h2 id="create-a-release">Create a release</h2>
  <p>
    From your project dashboard, choose <strong>Create release</strong>. Octopus
    assigns a version number based on your versioning strategy:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>Open the project and select <strong>Create release</strong>.</li>
    <li>Review the package versions selected for the release.</li>
    <li>Add release notes (optional but recommended).</li>
    <li>Select <strong>Save</strong>.</li>
  </ol>

  <figure class="image" data-image>
    <img
      class="image__img"
      src="/docs/img/getting-started.png"
      alt="The Create release screen in the Octopus dashboard"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <figcaption class="image__caption">
      The release editor, showing the package versions selected for this
      release.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h3 id="promote">Promote to an environment</h3>
  <p>
    Releases move through your lifecycle phases. The dashboard shows which
    environments a release has reached:
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Environment</th><th>Status</th><th>Last deployed</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Development</td>
        <td
          ><span class="status-pill status-pill--ok"
            ><span class="status-dot"></span>Success</span
          ></td
        >
        <td>2 hours ago</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Test</td>
        <td
          ><span class="status-pill status-pill--ok"
            ><span class="status-dot"></span>Success</span
          ></td
        >
        <td>1 hour ago</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Production</td>
        <td
          ><span class="status-pill status-pill--wait"
            ><span class="status-dot"></span>Awaiting approval</span
          ></td
        >
        <td>-</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <Callout intent="warning" title="Production gates">
    Deployments to <em>Production</em> in this lifecycle require manual approval.
    The release will pause until an authorized user intervenes.
  </Callout>

  <h2 id="deploy-cli">Deploy from the CLI</h2>
  <p>You can script the same flow with the Octopus CLI:</p>

  <CodeBlock label="Terminal" lang="bash"
    ><pre><code>octopus release deploy \
  --project "Web Store" \
  --version "2024.1.0" \
  --environment "Production" \
  --progress</code></pre></CodeBlock
  >

  <p>
    The <code>--progress</code> flag streams the deployment log to your terminal so
    it integrates cleanly with CI pipelines.
  </p>

  <Callout intent="success" title="Done">
    Once the deployment completes, the dashboard and the CLI both report a green
    <strong>Success</strong> status for that environment.
  </Callout>

  <h2 id="next-steps">Next steps</h2>

  <div class="not-prose mt-4 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
    <Card href="#" title="Deployment process →">
      Define the steps Octopus runs when it deploys your release.
    </Card>
    <Card href="#" title="Variables →">
      Parameterize deployments per environment, tenant, and target.
    </Card>
    <Card href="#" title="Runbooks →">
      Automate routine operations like backups and failover.
    </Card>
    <Card href="#" title="Channels →">
      Route releases through different lifecycles and rules.
    </Card>
  </div>

  <div class="not-prose mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
    <Button href="#" variant="primary">Read the deployment guide</Button>
    <Button href="#" variant="secondary">Browse the CLI reference</Button>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
